title: For Sale:  Genuine MRE's
postcontent: These are genuine mil-spec MRE's, not the cheap commercial wanna-be "camping meals".  There are two different cases (Case A and Case B).  Each case has a different assortment of 12 meals.  With 12 meals per case, at this price, it is only $4.58 a meal for food that you can take anywhere with no refrigeration and still have a hot meal with loads of accessories such as crackers/bread, cheese/jelly spread, coffee, sugar, creamer, gum, Tabasco sauce, matches, and even toilet paper!  These come with a water-activated heater for the entree, and detailed directions on how to use it.  I also have spare heaters that I will provide so that you can heat up accessories as well.  The dates on the boxes are the Re-inspect Date, not the expiration date.  Genuine MRE cases like these have a TTI (Time and Temperature Indicator) on the outside of the box to assist inspectors in determining if MREs are still good. There are two parts to the TTI – an outer dark circle and an inner light circle. As long as the inner circle is still lighter than the outside circle, the MREs are good.  Shown here is a picture of the actual TTI from one of the cases (and they all look like this).  As you can see, the center is much lighter than the Reference Ring, indicating that these case still have a lot of life left in them.  $55 per case or only $50 per case if you buy two or more cases.THESE ARE LEGAL TO OWN, so please don't be an internet lawyer and try to enforce a law that doesn't exist.

title: For Sale:  Palmetto Arms Full Auto Bolt Carrier Group
postcontent: This is a Palmetto Arms Full Auto Bolt Carrier Group for AR-15 Rifles and Pistols. It is new in the original tube. It has never been fire or installed. This will not make your rifle full auto. It will still be semi auto with this BCG installed. TO make your gun full auto you need this and an auto sear. The reason to have a full auto bolt is to slow the rediculously fast cycle rate of the AR-15 because the full auto BCG has more mass. This makes the gun much more manageable by decreasing perceived recoil allowing much more successful follow up shots. It also helps to reduce wear caused by the bolt slamming against the upper receiver and other parts. This will make your gun fire much smoother but it will NOT reduce it's rate of fire. It will fire just as fast as it always has it will just be smoother. These Palmetto BCG's are very high quality and certainly equal or better than any other mil-spec bolt carrier available. This has the Palmetto Arms crest laser engraved in the bolt carrier. See Pictures. I will ship this to anywhere in the USA where it is legal. It is up to you to find out if you local laws allow AR-15 parts. I personally don't know of any area where this would not be legal but there might be one or two places. title: For Sale:  Colt Model 1883 Hammerless Double Barrel 12 Gauge Shotgun
postcontent: The Model 1883 Hammerless Double Barrel Shotgun was made from 1883 to 1895, with approximately 7,360 manufactured.  The double barrel shotguns were usually custom made and fitted with damascus barrels from 28 to 32 inches in length.  Per the Blue Book of Gun Values regarding the Model 1883:  "This model was generally a custom order gun with no standard grades designated.  Quality was extremely high, and the cost of manufacture is a large reason why the gun never sold in large numbers commercially.  The Model 1883 was discontinued after only 12 years of manufacture (it was one of the most expesive shotgunns during its day)".  This 1883 is fitted with 30 inch damascus barrels, double triggers, finely checkered Walnut forearm with ebony tip, finely checkered and nicely figured Walnut stock fitted with a black hard rubber butt-plate, extensive engraving on the receiver, safety button, break-down lever, trigger guard, forearm takedown lever and framing, and a small portion of the barrel, color case-hardened receiver, and a dolls head rib extension.  What really sets this gun apart is the gold plaque on the side of the stock which states this gun was presented to a Augustus W. Mott by C.H. Colt (Samuel Colt's son) on March 9th 1889.  There is also an initial medallion on the bottom of the stock with the engraved initials A.W.M..  Included is the factory letter stating this gun was shipped to C.H. Colt on April 10, 1889.  A truly one of a kind Colt firearm that is in excellent original condition.
